@anchor{mathml_non_numeric_subscripts}
@defvr {Option variable} mathml_non_numeric_subscripts
Default value: @code{false}

When @code{mathml_non_numeric_subscripts} is @code{true} and @code{mathml_underscore_is_subscript}, an underscore is treated as a subscript unconditionally.
The default is that only substrings of digits are subscripts.

@c ===beg===
@c load(mathml) $
@c (mathml_non_numeric_subscripts:false, mathml_underscore_is_subscript:true) $
@c mathml(a_variable_name);
@c mathml(a_variable_name_1_2);
@c mathml_non_numeric_subscripts:true $
@c mathml(a_variable_name);
@c mathml(a_variable_name_1_2);
@c ===end===
@example
(%i1) load(mathml) $
(%i2) (mathml_non_numeric_subscripts:false, mathml_underscore_is_subscript:true) $
(%i3) mathml(a_variable_name);
 <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mi>a_variable_name</mi>  </math>
(%o3)                           false
(%i4) mathml(a_variable_name_1_2);
 <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <msub><mi>a_variable_name</mi> <msub><mi> 1 </mi> <mi> 2 </mi>   </msub></msub></math>
(%o4)                           false
(%i5) mathml_non_numeric_subscripts:true $
(%i6) mathml(a_variable_name);
 <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <msub><mi>a</mi> <msub><mi> variable </mi> <mi> name </mi>   </msub></msub></math>
(%o6)                           false
(%i7) mathml(a_variable_name_1_2);
 <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <msub><mi>a</mi> <msub><mi> variable </mi> <msub><mi> name </mi> <msub><mi> 1 </mi> <mi> 2 </mi>   </msub></msub></msub></msub></math>
@end example
@end defvr

@anchor{mathml_underscore_is_subscript}
@defvr {Option variable} mathml_underscore_is_subscript
Default value: @code{false}

When @code{mathml_non_numeric_subscripts} is @code{true}. In this case,
when @code{mathml_underscore_is_subscript} is @code{false},
@code{mathml} treats an underscore as part of a symbol and only trailing
digits in the symbol name are treated as subscripts; when @code{true},
all underscores in a symbol name are treated as if they begin a
subscript; otherwise, when @code{mathml_underscore_is_subscript} is a
positive integer @var{n}, the first @var{n} underscores in a symbol name
(counting from the right) are treated as subscripts and any remaining
subscripts are treated as ordinary characters.

When @code{mathml_non_numeric_subscripts} is @code{false}, the above
description is accurate for the right-most part of the symbol name that
contains only digits and underscores (compare the lines following
@code{%i4} and @code{%i7} in the above example).

@c ===beg===
@c load(mathml) $
@c mathml_underscore_is_subscript:false $
@c mathml(x_1);
@c mathml_underscore_is_subscript:1 $
@c mathml(x_1);
@c mathml(x_1_2);
@c ===end===
@ifnothtml
@example
(%i1) load(mathml) $
(%i2) mathml_underscore_is_subscript:false $
